The database focuses on the main business entity, which is a financial transaction. Every transaction is assigned to exactly one category, and can be efficiently grouped and filtered for analytics without having to store duplicate strings. Users are stored in a separate table from the numbers and names, preventing duplicate records in thousands of rows of transactions, and will enable future options such as user profiles or fraud detection. There is nothing special about the many-to-many relationship between users and transactions; a user may be a part of thousands of transactions, and a transaction always has two users: one as sender and one as receiver. This can be solved by using a transaction_participants junction table with one role column (SENDER/RECEIVER), to keep the schema clean and queryable. The system_logs table is completely divorced from the business data, and it logs activity from the ETL pipeline without contaminating the transactional data, in line with separation of concerns; Indexes are placed on foreign keys and often used in filters (transaction_date, status, phone_number) to enhance the performance of dashboards. CHECK constraints ensure that values are valid (>= 0) and that status/role values are valid, which can be done at the database level instead of just the application level of logic.